Overview
This project implements a pixel-based image classification system for satellite imagery using the Maximum Likelihood Classification (MLC) algorithm. 
Each pixel is represented by its RGB values and classified into predefined surface categories based on statistical modeling.
The goal is to transform raw image data into a structured and meaningful classification map.
Each pixel is represented as:
x = [R, G, B]
Classes: Sea, Tree, Road, Field, Sand

Objectives
Classify satellite image pixels into distinct surface classes
Apply a Gaussian probabilistic model for classification
Analyze how training sample selection affects classification accuracy
Compare different sampling strategies for better results
This project classifies a satellite image using the Maximum Likelihood Classification (MLC) method.

Process
Select sample pixels for each class
Compute mean and covariance
Classify each pixel based on probability

Sampling
Random sampling
Manual click sampling
Coordinate-based sampling

✔ Best result: Coordinate-based sampling

📈 Results
Good separation: Sea, Sand
Some overlap: Tree, Field

Tech - Python, NumPy, OpenCV, Matplotlib
